WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.940 align:middle line:90%


00:00:09.940 --> 00:00:13.419 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:13.419 --> 00:00:24.888 align:middle line:90%


00:00:24.888 --> 00:00:26.680 align:middle line:10%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:26.680 --> 00:00:28.900 align:middle line:10%
You know, we have
many incredible guests

00:00:28.900 --> 00:00:31.880 align:middle line:10%
on this program, and
we have over the years.

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:33.550 align:middle line:10%
But in this program
today, we're going

00:00:33.550 --> 00:00:36.130 align:middle line:10%
to talk with an individual
who is on the cutting

00:00:36.130 --> 00:00:38.950 align:middle line:10%
edge of where we
will be in terms

00:00:38.950 --> 00:00:40.510 align:middle line:10%
of the future of humanity.

00:00:40.510 --> 00:00:42.280 align:middle line:10%
His name is Daniel Pinchbeck.

00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:43.990 align:middle line:10%
He's the bestselling
author of "Breaking

00:00:43.990 --> 00:00:49.510 align:middle line:10%
Open the Head," "2012, The
Return of Quetzalcoatl,"

00:00:49.510 --> 00:00:50.770 align:middle line:10%
and "How Soon is Now?"

00:00:50.770 --> 00:00:53.680 align:middle line:10%
And his new book is called
"When Plants Dream."

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:56.590 align:middle line:10%
He's featured in the
2010 documentary,

00:00:56.590 --> 00:00:59.000 align:middle line:10%
"2012, Time for Change."

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:01.240 align:middle line:10%
And he's one of the most
incredible human minds

00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:02.080 align:middle line:10%
I've ever talked to.

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:03.700 align:middle line:84%
Daniel, welcome to
"Beyond Belief."

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:05.379 align:middle line:84%
>>DANIEL PINCHBECK: Yeah, thank
you for those nice accolades.

00:01:05.379 --> 00:01:06.370 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How've you been?

00:01:06.370 --> 00:01:07.440 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: I've been
good-- good, yeah.

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:09.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Boy, this planet
continues to change and evolve,

00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:10.740 align:middle line:90%
doesn't it?

00:01:10.740 --> 00:01:13.210 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: It seems
like it's doing something.

00:01:13.210 --> 00:01:17.660 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: You have looked at what
we call ecological emergencies

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:18.460 align:middle line:10%
on this planet.

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:19.880 align:middle line:10%
What do you mean by that?

00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:20.680 align:middle line:10%
>>PINCHBECK: Yeah.

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:22.970 align:middle line:10%
Well, I mean, it's
not just me obviously.

00:01:22.970 --> 00:01:25.150 align:middle line:10%
The UN just issued
a report recently

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:28.240 align:middle line:10%
saying that we had
about 10 to 12 years

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:31.780 align:middle line:10%
to make a major shift
in the amount of CO2

00:01:31.780 --> 00:01:34.495 align:middle line:10%
that we're producing
if we are going

00:01:34.495 --> 00:01:38.650 align:middle line:10%
to avoid catastrophic
warming and temperature rise.

00:01:38.650 --> 00:01:41.110 align:middle line:84%
And many scientists
already believe

00:01:41.110 --> 00:01:45.640 align:middle line:84%
that it's too late to prevent
really catastrophic effects.

00:01:45.640 --> 00:01:49.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Are we in an earth
cycle, or is this all man-made?

00:01:49.330 --> 00:01:53.248 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well, yeah, I
think that's a good question.

00:01:53.248 --> 00:01:54.790 align:middle line:84%
Maybe some of both,
but we definitely

00:01:54.790 --> 00:01:57.380 align:middle line:84%
can attribute it
to human causes.

00:01:57.380 --> 00:01:59.560 align:middle line:84%
I know there are
some commentators who

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:00.880 align:middle line:90%
still argue against that.

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:03.430 align:middle line:84%
But you know, we put
a million tons of CO2

00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:05.080 align:middle line:90%
into the atmosphere every hour.

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:07.960 align:middle line:84%
We can measure the amount
of CO2 in the atmosphere.

00:02:07.960 --> 00:02:11.283 align:middle line:84%
We know the impact
that we're having.

00:02:11.283 --> 00:02:13.200 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of what we're
doing is pretty clear--

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:14.903 align:middle line:90%
I mean, also deforestation.

00:02:14.903 --> 00:02:17.070 align:middle line:84%
And then we're seeing forest
fires around the world.

00:02:17.070 --> 00:02:19.780 align:middle line:84%
So even now, I think we're 1.2
Celsius warmer, or something

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:21.910 align:middle line:84%
like that, than we were
in pre-industrial times.

00:02:21.910 --> 00:02:22.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Well, that's a lot too.

00:02:22.870 --> 00:02:23.960 align:middle line:90%
That's a big increase.

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:27.400 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Yes, but if
we go to 2, 3 degrees,

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:30.550 align:middle line:90%
it truly could be catastrophic.

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:34.540 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, we're learning how meshed
together the fabric of life

00:02:34.540 --> 00:02:37.030 align:middle line:84%
is on the planet
as, unfortunately,

00:02:37.030 --> 00:02:40.042 align:middle line:84%
our industrial civilization is
kind of tearing it to shreds.

00:02:40.042 --> 00:02:41.500 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You know,
mankind has been

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:44.200 align:middle line:84%
pumping all kinds of
things into the atmosphere

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:46.720 align:middle line:90%
since the Industrial Revolution.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:50.020 align:middle line:84%
In the earlier days, during
the dinosaur era and stuff,

00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:51.490 align:middle line:90%
we had a lot of CO2 too.

00:02:51.490 --> 00:02:56.330 align:middle line:10%
So those people who are against
man-made ecological change

00:02:56.330 --> 00:02:59.560 align:middle line:10%
will use those reasons to cite.

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:01.370 align:middle line:90%
How do we argue with that?

00:03:01.370 --> 00:03:02.170 align:middle line:90%
>>PINCHBECK: What?

00:03:02.170 --> 00:03:04.070 align:middle line:84%
You mean there was more
CO2 in other epochs?

00:03:04.070 --> 00:03:04.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Mm-hmm.

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:06.700 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well, yeah,
but the whole climate

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:07.640 align:middle line:90%
was totally different.

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:09.473 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we've been in
the sort of Goldilocks

00:03:09.473 --> 00:03:12.250 align:middle line:84%
period where we've been
very lucky that we've

00:03:12.250 --> 00:03:14.620 align:middle line:84%
had a few 100,000 years
with a climate that

00:03:14.620 --> 00:03:17.770 align:middle line:84%
has been very temperate and has
allowed for human civilization

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:19.290 align:middle line:90%
to evolve in this way.

00:03:19.290 --> 00:03:21.520 align:middle line:84%
And now we've thrown things
radically out of balance.

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:23.920 align:middle line:84%
And what I argue in
"How Soon Is Now?"

00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:26.980 align:middle line:84%
is that unless we
really undertook this

00:03:26.980 --> 00:03:30.610 align:middle line:84%
as a collective project
for the future of humanity

00:03:30.610 --> 00:03:32.440 align:middle line:84%
and the sake of
the planet, we're

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:35.060 align:middle line:84%
probably going to go into
extinction in the next century

00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:35.860 align:middle line:90%
or so.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:36.550 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oh my god.

00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:37.360 align:middle line:90%
>>PINCHBECK: Yeah.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:39.100 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When you
say extinction,

00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:40.890 align:middle line:84%
you're saying that's
it for all of us.

00:03:40.890 --> 00:03:43.930 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well, I mean
the problem is that--

00:03:43.930 --> 00:03:47.800 align:middle line:84%
so for instance,
oxygen. Like, the Amazon

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:50.480 align:middle line:84%
produces 20% of our oxygen.
The plankton in the ocean--

00:03:50.480 --> 00:03:51.730 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: For the whole planet?

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:52.530 align:middle line:90%
>>PINCHBECK: Yeah.

00:03:52.530 --> 00:03:54.310 align:middle line:84%
The plankton in
the ocean produced

00:03:54.310 --> 00:03:56.800 align:middle line:84%
60% of the oxygen
we breathe roughly.

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:01.150 align:middle line:84%
So you know, if we go to 2
to 3 degrees Celsius warmer,

00:04:01.150 --> 00:04:03.910 align:middle line:84%
we lose about 40% of the
Amazon just from the heat.

00:04:03.910 --> 00:04:06.340 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we're already
deforesting the Amazon.

00:04:06.340 --> 00:04:08.920 align:middle line:84%
We're losing seven football
fields of jungle per minute,

00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:11.020 align:middle line:84%
according to some
estimates, every day.

00:04:11.020 --> 00:04:13.720 align:middle line:84%
So we'd lose at least
10% of our oxygen

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:16.160 align:middle line:90%
from what happens to the Amazon.

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:18.399 align:middle line:84%
Plus the plankton in the
ocean, their life cycle

00:04:18.399 --> 00:04:20.980 align:middle line:84%
is also being negatively
impacted by the amount of CO2

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:24.520 align:middle line:90%
that the oceans are taking in.

00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:27.380 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, we could really
sort of asphyxiate ourselves.

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:30.040 align:middle line:84%
And we know there's
been massive species

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:31.040 align:middle line:90%
extinctions in the past.

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:35.810 align:middle line:84%
It's just unfortunate because
if we were to collectively shift

00:04:35.810 --> 00:04:37.990 align:middle line:84%
this direction-- basically
what I argue in the book,

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:41.380 align:middle line:84%
and which many non-profit
movements are now saying,

00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:43.930 align:middle line:84%
is that we need a
climate mobilization.

00:04:43.930 --> 00:04:46.840 align:middle line:84%
We need to look at what
the US did in World War II

00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:49.600 align:middle line:84%
after Pearl Harbor
bombing, when they shifted

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.790 align:middle line:84%
all of the industrial
manufacturing

00:04:51.790 --> 00:04:54.760 align:middle line:84%
from everything else they were
doing-- toys, personal cars,

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:56.830 align:middle line:84%
or whatever-- it all
went into the war effort.

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:57.747 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:04:57.747 --> 00:04:59.930 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: So this
would be the opposite.

00:04:59.930 --> 00:05:01.990 align:middle line:84%
It would have to be almost
a global effort where

00:05:01.990 --> 00:05:03.500 align:middle line:84%
we would say, OK,
we're all going

00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:06.610 align:middle line:84%
to sink together
unless we massively

00:05:06.610 --> 00:05:10.760 align:middle line:84%
redirect our social
powers, our creativity,

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:14.140 align:middle line:84%
our technical capacities,
our resources to making

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:15.990 align:middle line:90%
a regenerative system.

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:17.740 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Do you think
the planet can react

00:05:17.740 --> 00:05:20.095 align:middle line:10%
quickly once that happens?

00:05:20.095 --> 00:05:21.970 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well, I
mean, some of the damage

00:05:21.970 --> 00:05:23.178 align:middle line:90%
is already locked into place.

00:05:23.178 --> 00:05:25.590 align:middle line:84%
I don't think we're going
to be able to prevent

00:05:25.590 --> 00:05:27.330 align:middle line:84%
the loss of a lot
of the coastal land

00:05:27.330 --> 00:05:30.400 align:middle line:84%
from flooding and so on
over 50 years or something.

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:31.620 align:middle line:90%
But we don't know.

00:05:31.620 --> 00:05:33.990 align:middle line:84%
We are a very, very
creative species.

00:05:33.990 --> 00:05:36.180 align:middle line:90%
And we just have to--

00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:40.590 align:middle line:84%
you know, the smartphone
was impossible 30 years ago,

00:05:40.590 --> 00:05:43.140 align:middle line:90%
and then they figured it out.

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:46.080 align:middle line:84%
On the negative side, the atom
bomb required this huge coming

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:46.880 align:middle line:90%
together.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:48.297 align:middle line:84%
But essentially,
at the moment, we

00:05:48.297 --> 00:05:52.290 align:middle line:84%
have a political and
corporate structure

00:05:52.290 --> 00:05:56.580 align:middle line:84%
that is obstructing our capacity
to focus our energy where

00:05:56.580 --> 00:05:57.870 align:middle line:90%
it needs to focus.

00:05:57.870 --> 00:06:00.362 align:middle line:84%
And we're in kind of
like a trance of denial

00:06:00.362 --> 00:06:01.320 align:middle line:90%
about what's happening.

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:03.090 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: In your book,
"How Soon is Now?"

00:06:03.090 --> 00:06:07.335 align:middle line:84%
you take a look at
this ecological crisis.

00:06:07.335 --> 00:06:10.305 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:10.305 --> 00:06:13.280 align:middle line:90%


00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:15.080 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: My name
is Daniel Pinchbeck.

00:06:15.080 --> 00:06:17.100 align:middle line:90%
I was born in New York City.

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:21.715 align:middle line:10%
I'm a writer and a thinker
and sometimes an entrepreneur.

00:06:21.715 --> 00:06:24.450 align:middle line:90%


00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:28.140 align:middle line:10%
"How Soon is Now" looks
at the ecological crisis

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:30.540 align:middle line:10%
as a kind of rite of
passage or initiation

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:34.710 align:middle line:10%
for the human species to reach
another level of consciousness

00:06:34.710 --> 00:06:35.985 align:middle line:10%
and another level of society.

00:06:35.985 --> 00:06:39.690 align:middle line:90%


00:06:39.690 --> 00:06:43.040 align:middle line:84%
One of the main things that
compelled me to write this book

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:46.085 align:middle line:84%
is a study of the evidence
around the ecological crisis.

00:06:46.085 --> 00:06:48.910 align:middle line:90%


00:06:48.910 --> 00:06:51.493 align:middle line:10%
We find ourselves in this
very powerful country,

00:06:51.493 --> 00:06:53.410 align:middle line:10%
if you live in the United
States, who has just

00:06:53.410 --> 00:06:56.980 align:middle line:10%
elected a president
who denies that we

00:06:56.980 --> 00:07:00.480 align:middle line:10%
are in a crisis of ecology
and climate and so on.

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:03.100 align:middle line:84%
But the evidence from a vast
preponderance of scientists

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:05.730 align:middle line:84%
is that we have passed a lot of
critical thresholds and tipping

00:07:05.730 --> 00:07:06.530 align:middle line:90%
points.

00:07:06.530 --> 00:07:11.800 align:middle line:90%


00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:15.390 align:middle line:84%
We're also losing 10% of the
Earth's remaining biodiversity

00:07:15.390 --> 00:07:17.406 align:middle line:90%
every 10 to 15 years.

00:07:17.406 --> 00:07:21.760 align:middle line:84%
We're losing 100 to 150 species
a day out of little more than 8

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:25.120 align:middle line:90%
million total species.

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:28.570 align:middle line:84%
And we now know how tightly
meshed together the web of life

00:07:28.570 --> 00:07:29.800 align:middle line:90%
is on the planet.

00:07:29.800 --> 00:07:32.440 align:middle line:10%
So as we pull it
apart, eventually it's

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:35.770 align:middle line:10%
going to break down, and
we'll enter a different cycle

00:07:35.770 --> 00:07:37.780 align:middle line:10%
where the Earth just
won't be very hospitable

00:07:37.780 --> 00:07:40.660 align:middle line:10%
and won't support large
mammals such as ourselves.

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:44.910 align:middle line:90%


00:07:44.910 --> 00:07:48.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And regardless, Daniel,
of how we got there, I think

00:07:48.270 --> 00:07:50.545 align:middle line:84%
there's no argument
that it's happening.

00:07:50.545 --> 00:07:51.420 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's obvious.

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:53.370 align:middle line:90%
The data is the data.

00:07:53.370 --> 00:07:57.990 align:middle line:10%
Why can't we come together
as a world and say,

00:07:57.990 --> 00:07:59.340 align:middle line:10%
we have a problem--

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:00.510 align:middle line:10%
we all admit it--

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:02.970 align:middle line:10%
how we got to it,
that's debatable.

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:03.840 align:middle line:90%
But let's fix--

00:08:03.840 --> 00:08:04.410 align:middle line:90%
>>PINCHBECK: It's not debatable.

00:08:04.410 --> 00:08:05.110 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --but let's
fix the problem.

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:06.460 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: It's actually
not very debatable.

00:08:06.460 --> 00:08:07.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Well, I know.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:07.770 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: It's
very straightforward.

00:08:07.770 --> 00:08:09.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But there is that camp
that will always fight that.

00:08:09.580 --> 00:08:11.520 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Yeah, but that
camp happens to be not dealing

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:12.395 align:middle line:90%
with actual evidence.

00:08:12.395 --> 00:08:14.810 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But why does that
camp say and admit there

00:08:14.810 --> 00:08:15.610 align:middle line:90%
is a problem.

00:08:15.610 --> 00:08:17.010 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: The
reason is basically

00:08:17.010 --> 00:08:19.350 align:middle line:84%
we have an operating system
for our global civilization

00:08:19.350 --> 00:08:22.200 align:middle line:84%
that's based on
corporations that

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:24.090 align:middle line:84%
make money based on
quarterly earnings

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:25.710 align:middle line:90%
and short-term profits.

00:08:25.710 --> 00:08:29.280 align:middle line:84%
And so if the function
of those corporations--

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:32.280 align:middle line:84%
in a way they're like robots
or like artificial lifeforms.

00:08:32.280 --> 00:08:36.780 align:middle line:84%
They have to keep forcing
increased profits.

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:43.710 align:middle line:84%
And the way to do that requires
getting more consumer goods,

00:08:43.710 --> 00:08:47.100 align:middle line:84%
extracting more natural
resources, and so on.

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:50.010 align:middle line:84%
So we have an extractive and
exploitative economic model.

00:08:50.010 --> 00:08:53.160 align:middle line:84%
And that's not going to
give us the opportunity

00:08:53.160 --> 00:08:56.130 align:middle line:84%
to address the crisis we're
facing at the base level

00:08:56.130 --> 00:08:58.110 align:middle line:90%
that we have to address it at.

00:08:58.110 --> 00:09:01.333 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Are we learning
anything from this disaster?

00:09:01.333 --> 00:09:03.750 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well, I mean,
there's a lot of amazing things

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:04.890 align:middle line:90%
happening--

00:09:04.890 --> 00:09:07.350 align:middle line:84%
incredible developments
and technologies, solar.

00:09:07.350 --> 00:09:08.150 align:middle line:90%
I mean, we know--

00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:09.483 align:middle line:90%
as I write in "How Soon is Now?"

00:09:09.483 --> 00:09:11.120 align:middle line:90%
I look in every area.

00:09:11.120 --> 00:09:12.597 align:middle line:84%
We know all of
the things that we

00:09:12.597 --> 00:09:14.430 align:middle line:84%
would have to do to
actually deal with this.

00:09:14.430 --> 00:09:17.850 align:middle line:84%
Like, we have to shift
from industrial farming

00:09:17.850 --> 00:09:21.360 align:middle line:84%
back to no-till
agriculture, permaculture.

00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:24.270 align:middle line:84%
They are much more
labor intensive.

00:09:24.270 --> 00:09:28.470 align:middle line:84%
We have to shift to
renewable energy obviously,

00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:31.080 align:middle line:90%
cradle to cradle manufacturing--

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:33.810 align:middle line:84%
I mean, in every area we know
what we would need to do.

00:09:33.810 --> 00:09:36.000 align:middle line:84%
It's just that we
haven't summoned up

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:39.775 align:middle line:84%
the collective will, and there's
a kind of blockage in people.

00:09:39.775 --> 00:09:41.400 align:middle line:10%
You know, you're just
mentioning you're

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:42.570 align:middle line:10%
having a great granddaughter.

00:09:42.570 --> 00:09:42.960 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:44.820 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well, sadly,
unless we address this,

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:47.278 align:middle line:84%
she's not really going to have
a world that's going to be--

00:09:47.278 --> 00:09:49.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, what
do we give them?

00:09:49.050 --> 00:09:50.592 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: So that
that's what I've

00:09:50.592 --> 00:09:53.820 align:middle line:84%
been trying to do in my
work over the last 10 years.

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:55.910 align:middle line:84%
I'd written a
bestselling book, "2012."

00:09:55.910 --> 00:10:00.240 align:middle line:84%
I could have become a kind
of different type of Tony

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:04.740 align:middle line:84%
Robbins-ish figure,
talking about how everybody

00:10:04.740 --> 00:10:07.150 align:middle line:84%
can have maximum
success and live

00:10:07.150 --> 00:10:08.590 align:middle line:90%
the secret and all that stuff.

00:10:08.590 --> 00:10:11.490 align:middle line:84%
But actually, I became much
more concerned with the fact

00:10:11.490 --> 00:10:13.860 align:middle line:84%
that our hyper-individual
culture based

00:10:13.860 --> 00:10:16.200 align:middle line:84%
on this destructive
economic system

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:18.550 align:middle line:84%
was really killing the
planet for our descendants,

00:10:18.550 --> 00:10:21.270 align:middle line:84%
and I still really
can't fathom why

00:10:21.270 --> 00:10:22.800 align:middle line:84%
everybody's attention
hasn't shifted

00:10:22.800 --> 00:10:24.160 align:middle line:90%
in that direction at this point.

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:25.410 align:middle line:90%
But I understand it also.

00:10:25.410 --> 00:10:27.390 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is it fixable?

00:10:27.390 --> 00:10:29.460 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: It's
not really fixable,

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:32.530 align:middle line:84%
but it's certainly something
that we need to address.

00:10:32.530 --> 00:10:35.370 align:middle line:84%
In the book "2012, The
Return of Quetzalcoatl,"

00:10:35.370 --> 00:10:38.040 align:middle line:84%
I also looked at it from
the more metaphysical side

00:10:38.040 --> 00:10:41.220 align:middle line:84%
of the street, like looking
at the indigenous prophecies

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:43.140 align:middle line:84%
of cultures like the
Hopi and the Maya.

00:10:43.140 --> 00:10:44.250 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, what
did they teach us?

00:10:44.250 --> 00:10:44.760 align:middle line:90%
>>PINCHBECK: What's that?

00:10:44.760 --> 00:10:46.150 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What did they teach
us, these indigenous people?

00:10:46.150 --> 00:10:49.110 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well, they
talked about transition.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:51.672 align:middle line:84%
Like, the Maya talked
about the fourth world--

00:10:51.672 --> 00:10:53.630 align:middle line:84%
the Hopi talked about
the fourth world entering

00:10:53.630 --> 00:10:54.940 align:middle line:90%
into the fifth world.

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:57.630 align:middle line:84%
The Nahuatl, the Aztecs, talked
about the age of the fifth sun

00:10:57.630 --> 00:10:59.120 align:middle line:90%
and the age of the sixth sun.

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:01.140 align:middle line:84%
So they understood
that we were going

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:03.450 align:middle line:84%
to go through this intense
transformational process.

00:11:03.450 --> 00:11:07.230 align:middle line:84%
I mean, according to some
of the Aztec prophecies,

00:11:07.230 --> 00:11:11.730 align:middle line:84%
we're shifting from a sun of
light to a sun of darkness.

00:11:11.730 --> 00:11:14.220 align:middle line:84%
And in their understanding
of the cyclical movements

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:17.370 align:middle line:84%
of energies and so
on, the sun of light

00:11:17.370 --> 00:11:21.540 align:middle line:84%
is more of a time where
waking consciousness,

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:23.910 align:middle line:84%
rationality, interest
in the material world,

00:11:23.910 --> 00:11:27.270 align:middle line:84%
those become
mankind's fixations.

00:11:27.270 --> 00:11:30.442 align:middle line:84%
And during the time when it's
back into a sun of darkness,

00:11:30.442 --> 00:11:32.400 align:middle line:84%
it's more about the
dreamworld and the psychic,

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:34.590 align:middle line:84%
and we realize that
reality becomes

00:11:34.590 --> 00:11:36.120 align:middle line:84%
more like a waking
dream, where it's

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:40.260 align:middle line:84%
more permeable to our intentions
and our thoughts and so on.

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:42.900 align:middle line:84%
So I feel many
people are grasping

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:45.060 align:middle line:84%
this, more and more
people in Western society.

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:48.000 align:middle line:84%
They use concepts like
synchronicity or manifestation.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.580 align:middle line:84%
So that is one element
of what's happening,

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:52.240 align:middle line:90%
and that is fascinating to me.

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:56.190 align:middle line:84%
But the other element is that
we have to address this system

00:11:56.190 --> 00:11:57.643 align:middle line:90%
crash that we've created.

00:11:57.643 --> 00:11:59.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: In your book
"How Soon is Now?"

00:11:59.310 --> 00:12:01.480 align:middle line:10%
you kind of tie in
human consciousness

00:12:01.480 --> 00:12:02.280 align:middle line:10%
with some of this.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:04.390 align:middle line:90%
How does that work?

00:12:04.390 --> 00:12:07.320 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: In the book, I
talk about visiting a community

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:09.570 align:middle line:84%
in Colombia,
indigenous community.

00:12:09.570 --> 00:12:11.910 align:middle line:84%
We worked with the Kogi
and the Arawak people, who

00:12:11.910 --> 00:12:14.160 align:middle line:84%
live high up in the
mountains of Colombia,

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:17.620 align:middle line:90%
and they come down to meet us.

00:12:17.620 --> 00:12:19.845 align:middle line:84%
They walk, like, 25 hours
down from the mountain top.

00:12:19.845 --> 00:12:20.645 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 25 hours?

00:12:20.645 --> 00:12:21.645 align:middle line:90%
>>PINCHBECK: Yeah, yeah.

00:12:21.645 --> 00:12:24.360 align:middle line:84%
And they basically were
trying to convey to us

00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:25.873 align:middle line:90%
that from their perspective--

00:12:25.873 --> 00:12:28.290 align:middle line:84%
there's actually a really good
film about them called "The

00:12:28.290 --> 00:12:29.832 align:middle line:84%
Elder Brothers'
Warning to Humanity."

00:12:29.832 --> 00:12:30.720 align:middle line:90%
It's worth seeing.

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:33.360 align:middle line:84%
They see themselves as an elder
civilization, like pre-Incan,

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:36.540 align:middle line:84%
and they see our civilization
as like a younger one, immature.

00:12:36.540 --> 00:12:39.000 align:middle line:84%
But they said that,
from their perspective,

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:43.230 align:middle line:84%
what we experience as reality
is a direct reflection

00:12:43.230 --> 00:12:47.720 align:middle line:84%
of our level of spirituality
and consciousness development.

00:12:47.720 --> 00:12:50.340 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
very fascinating.

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:52.970 align:middle line:84%
And when you see them,
really the elders

00:12:52.970 --> 00:12:57.260 align:middle line:84%
in that tribe, every movement
they make is very graceful.

00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:00.740 align:middle line:84%
You feel like they're
always in sacred time.

00:13:00.740 --> 00:13:04.020 align:middle line:84%
Whereas we've created this whole
idea of profane time and work

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:04.820 align:middle line:90%
time.

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:08.210 align:middle line:84%
And we're very rarely
in sacred time.

00:13:08.210 --> 00:13:10.632 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Are they aware
of what we're doing

00:13:10.632 --> 00:13:11.465 align:middle line:10%
to the environment--

00:13:11.465 --> 00:13:11.810 align:middle line:10%
>>PINCHBECK: Yeah.

00:13:11.810 --> 00:13:13.400 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --these
indigenous people?

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:14.390 align:middle line:90%
How do they sense that?

00:13:14.390 --> 00:13:15.770 align:middle line:90%
How do they know it's us?

00:13:15.770 --> 00:13:17.853 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well, the
indigenous people have been

00:13:17.853 --> 00:13:19.248 align:middle line:90%
aware, all around the planet--

00:13:19.248 --> 00:13:21.290 align:middle line:84%
well, first of all, I
mean, we've colonized them.

00:13:21.290 --> 00:13:22.220 align:middle line:90%
We've exploited them.

00:13:22.220 --> 00:13:24.020 align:middle line:84%
We've driven them
out of their lands.

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:26.780 align:middle line:84%
So they understand that we are
a culture that's based on--

00:13:26.780 --> 00:13:27.200 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Taking.

00:13:27.200 --> 00:13:28.617 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: --what
the Algonquins

00:13:28.617 --> 00:13:32.660 align:middle line:84%
call "wetiko," which is kind
of like a vampiric, parasitic

00:13:32.660 --> 00:13:38.440 align:middle line:84%
consciousness, or spirit, that
seeks to exploit and devour.

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:41.630 align:middle line:84%
And, yeah, the indigenous
cultures all around the world

00:13:41.630 --> 00:13:43.730 align:middle line:84%
have been the first
line of defense

00:13:43.730 --> 00:13:47.800 align:middle line:84%
in terms of the planet's
ecological resources--

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:50.390 align:middle line:84%
the Ogoni people in Nigeria
who were assassinated

00:13:50.390 --> 00:13:53.660 align:middle line:84%
by the oil companies
and so on, in Ecuador,

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:57.870 align:middle line:84%
the local tribes who were
poisoned by Texaco and so on.

00:13:57.870 --> 00:13:58.670 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sheesh.

00:13:58.670 --> 00:13:59.600 align:middle line:84%
>>PINCHBECK: Well,
but that's how

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:00.892 align:middle line:90%
we keep our thing going, right?

00:14:00.892 --> 00:14:02.540 align:middle line:90%
Like, you flew here today.

00:14:02.540 --> 00:14:05.050 align:middle line:90%
I flew here last night.

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:07.610 align:middle line:84%
We're part of this
whole machinery

00:14:07.610 --> 00:14:09.748 align:middle line:84%
of extraction and
exploitation, unfortunately.

00:14:09.748 --> 00:14:11.790 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: "How Soon is
Now?" your book, of course,

00:14:11.790 --> 00:14:15.907 align:middle line:84%
looks at a range of solutions
to the ecological emergency.

00:14:15.907 --> 00:14:17.240 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look at this topic.

00:14:17.240 --> 00:14:22.050 align:middle line:90%


00:14:22.050 --> 00:14:23.058 align:middle line:90%
